Peak Progression Analysis

Model the seasonal progression of the latitudinal peak in zooplankton carbon and net primary production.

Objectives:

  • Extract peak latitude for each day (2005-2024)
  • Visualize peak progression over time
  • Determine when peak is furthest south (ecological year boundary)
  • Model peak latitude as monotonically increasing function within each year

1. Setup and Load Data

In[5]:
# Create mask for California Current region
print("Creating spatial mask for California Current polygon...")

from shapely.geometry import Point

# Get the California Current polygon
cc_polygon = california_current.geometry.iloc[0]

# Create 2D mask array
lats = ds.latitude.values
lons = ds.longitude.values
mask = np.zeros((len(lats), len(lons)), dtype=bool)

# Check each grid point
for i, lat in enumerate(lats):
    for j, lon in enumerate(lons):
        point = Point(lon, lat)
        mask[i, j] = cc_polygon.contains(point)

print(f"Mask created: {mask.sum()} / {mask.size} grid points inside polygon ({100*mask.sum()/mask.size:.1f}%)")

# Apply mask to the dataset - set values outside polygon to NaN
ds_masked = ds.copy(deep=True)
for var in ds_masked.data_vars:
    # Broadcast mask to include time dimension
    mask_3d = np.broadcast_to(mask, ds_masked[var].shape)
    ds_masked[var].values = np.where(mask_3d, ds_masked[var].values, np.nan)

print("Mask applied to dataset")

# Replace ds with masked version
ds = ds_masked

In[7]:
# Find peak latitude for each day
print("Finding peak latitudes for each day...")

peak_data = []

for i in range(len(ds.time)):
    date = pd.Timestamp(ds.time.isel(time=i).values)
    
    # ZOOC peak
    zooc_profile = zooc_lon_mean.isel(time=i)
    zooc_peak_idx = zooc_profile.argmax().values
    zooc_peak_lat = ds.latitude.isel(latitude=zooc_peak_idx).values
    zooc_peak_val = zooc_profile.isel(latitude=zooc_peak_idx).values
    
    # NPP peak
    npp_profile = npp_lon_mean.isel(time=i)
    npp_peak_idx = npp_profile.argmax().values
    npp_peak_lat = ds.latitude.isel(latitude=npp_peak_idx).values
    npp_peak_val = npp_profile.isel(latitude=npp_peak_idx).values
    
    peak_data.append({
        'date': date,
        'year': date.year,
        'month': date.month,
        'day': date.day,
        'dayofyear': date.dayofyear,
        'zooc_peak_lat': zooc_peak_lat,
        'zooc_peak_val': zooc_peak_val,
        'npp_peak_lat': npp_peak_lat,
        'npp_peak_val': npp_peak_val
    })

# Create DataFrame
peaks_df = pd.DataFrame(peak_data)
print(f"Extracted peaks for {len(peaks_df)} days")
peaks_df.head()

5. Find Ecological Year Boundary (Peak Furthest South)

In[10]:
# Find when peak is furthest south on average
# Use rolling mean to smooth out daily variability
window = 30  # 30-day rolling mean

zooc_smooth = seasonal_mean_zooc.rolling(window=window, center=True).mean()
npp_smooth = seasonal_mean_npp.rolling(window=window, center=True).mean()

zooc_min_day = zooc_smooth.idxmin()
npp_min_day = npp_smooth.idxmin()

print(f"ZOOC peak furthest south: Day {zooc_min_day} ({pd.Timestamp('2024-01-01') + pd.Timedelta(days=int(zooc_min_day)-1):%B %d})")
print(f"NPP peak furthest south: Day {npp_min_day} ({pd.Timestamp('2024-01-01') + pd.Timedelta(days=int(npp_min_day)-1):%B %d})")

print(f"  ZOOC: {zooc_smooth.min():.2f}N")
print(f"  NPP: {npp_smooth.min():.2f}N")

6. Check Monotonicity Assumption

In[12]:
# For each variable, check if peak generally increases within ecological year
# Use the minimum from smoothed data as year boundary

def assign_ecological_year(row, year_start_day):
    """Assign ecological year based on year start day."""
    if row['dayofyear'] >= year_start_day:
        return row['year']
    else:
        return row['year'] - 1

# Assign ecological years
peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'] = peaks_df.apply(lambda r: assign_ecological_year(r, zooc_min_day), axis=1)
peaks_df['eco_year_npp'] = peaks_df.apply(lambda r: assign_ecological_year(r, npp_min_day), axis=1)

# Calculate day within ecological year
peaks_df['eco_dayofyear_zooc'] = peaks_df.apply(
    lambda r: (r['dayofyear'] - zooc_min_day) % 365, axis=1
)
peaks_df['eco_dayofyear_npp'] = peaks_df.apply(
    lambda r: (r['dayofyear'] - npp_min_day) % 365, axis=1
)

print("Ecological years assigned!")
print(f"ZOOC ecological years: {peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'].min()} to {peaks_df['eco_year_zooc'].max()}")
print(f"NPP ecological years: {peaks_df['eco_year_npp'].min()} to {peaks_df['eco_year_npp'].max()}")

Ecological years assigned!
ZOOC ecological years: 2004 to 2024
NPP ecological years: 2004 to 2024

7. Model: Day of Peak ~ Latitude + Year Random Effect

Model when each latitude reaches its annual peak as a monotonically increasing function of latitude.

In[17]:
# Compute peak timing for each latitude in each year separately
print("Computing peak timing by latitude and year...")

peak_timing_data = []

for year in range(2005, 2025):
    # Get data for this year
    year_mask = (dates.year == year)
    
    if not year_mask.any():
        continue
    
    zooc_year = zooc_profiles[year_mask, :]
    npp_year = npp_profiles[year_mask, :]
    doy_year = dayofyear_array[year_mask]
    
    # For each latitude
    for i, lat in enumerate(latitudes):
        # ZOOC
        if len(zooc_year[:, i]) > 0:
            zooc_max_idx = np.argmax(zooc_year[:, i])
            zooc_peak_doy = doy_year[zooc_max_idx]
            zooc_peak_val = zooc_year[zooc_max_idx, i]
            
            peak_timing_data.append({
                'latitude': lat,
                'year': year,
                'variable': 'zooc',
                'peak_doy': zooc_peak_doy,
                'peak_value': zooc_peak_val
            })
        
        # NPP
        if len(npp_year[:, i]) > 0:
            npp_max_idx = np.argmax(npp_year[:, i])
            npp_peak_doy = doy_year[npp_max_idx]
            npp_peak_val = npp_year[npp_max_idx, i]
            
            peak_timing_data.append({
                'latitude': lat,
                'year': year,
                'variable': 'npp',
                'peak_doy': npp_peak_doy,
                'peak_value': npp_peak_val
            })

# Create DataFrame
timing_df = pd.DataFrame(peak_timing_data)
print(f"Created dataset with {len(timing_df)} observations")
print(f"  {len(timing_df[timing_df['variable']=='zooc'])} ZOOC observations")
print(f"  {len(timing_df[timing_df['variable']=='npp'])} NPP observations")
timing_df.head()

In[19]:
# Fit GAM: peak_doy ~ s(latitude, constraints='monotonic_inc') + f(year)
# Monotonic constraint ensures peak timing increases with latitude (north)
print("Fitting ZOOC timing GAM with monotonic constraint...")
gam_zooc_timing = LinearGAM(s(0, n_splines=25, constraints='monotonic_inc') + f(1))
gam_zooc_timing.gridsearch(X_zooc_timing, y_zooc_timing)

print(f"ZOOC timing GAM fitted!")
print(f"  Pseudo R: {gam_zooc_timing.statistics_['pseudo_r2']['explained_deviance']:.4f}")
print(f"  AIC: {gam_zooc_timing.statistics_['AIC']:.2f}")

# Visualize timing models with latitude on y-axis
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 16))

# Generate prediction grids
lats_grid = np.arange(latitudes.min(), latitudes.max(), 0.5)
mean_year_timing = int(np.median(timing_df['year']))

# ZOOC - mean prediction with CI
X_grid_zooc_timing = np.column_stack([lats_grid, np.full(len(lats_grid), mean_year_timing)])
pred_zooc_timing = gam_zooc_timing.predict(X_grid_zooc_timing)
conf_zooc_timing = gam_zooc_timing.prediction_intervals(X_grid_zooc_timing, width=0.95)

axes[0, 0].plot(pred_zooc_timing, lats_grid, color='darkblue', linewidth=2, label='Mean prediction')
axes[0, 0].fill_betweenx(lats_grid, conf_zooc_timing[:, 0], conf_zooc_timing[:, 1],
                        alpha=0.2, color='steelblue', label='95% CI')
axes[0, 0].set_ylabel('Latitude (N)', fontsize=12)

axes[1, 0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)

# NPP - all years overlaid
for year in range(2005, 2024):
    X_grid_year = np.column_stack([lats_grid, np.full(len(lats_grid), year)])
    pred_year = gam_npp_timing.predict(X_grid_year)
    axes[1, 1].plot(pred_year, lats_grid, alpha=0.3, linewidth=1, color='darkgreen')

axes[1, 1].plot(pred_npp_timing, lats_grid, color='darkgreen', linewidth=3, label='Mean year')
axes[1, 1].set_ylabel('Latitude (N)', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 1].set_xlabel('Day of Year (when peak occurs)', fontsize=12)
axes[1, 1].set_title('NPP - All Years (showing year random effects)', 
                    fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
axes[1, 1].legend()
axes[1, 1].grid(True, alpha=0.3)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig(figures_dir / 'gam_timing_predictions.png', dpi=300, bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()
